Steam Games Analysis¶

Introduction¶

We are provided with a Steam Games Dataset,providing a rich tapestry of insights into the PC gaming realm. Our analysis delves into the dynamic interplay of genres, ownership statistics, and player engagement metrics, aiming to decipher the evolving landscape of gaming preferences and how game developers could benefit from this and tried to dig out many trends.

Understanding the data¶

The dataset contains the following columns, each representing different attributes of games on the Steam platform:

  • AppID: Unique identifier for each game.
  • Name: Name of the game.
  • Release date: Date when the game was released.
  • Estimated owners: Estimated range of how many people own the game.
  • Peak CCU: Peak concurrent users playing the game.
  • Required age: Age requirement to play the game.
  • Price: Price of the game in USD.
  • DLC count: Number of downloadable content items available for the game.
  • About the game: Description of the game.
  • Supported languages: Languages supported by the game.
  • Full audio languages: Languages available in full audio.
  • Reviews: Text reviews of the game.
  • Header image: URL to the game's header image.
  • Website: URL to the game's official website.
  • Support url: URL for game support.
  • Support email: Email address for game support.
  • Windows, Mac, Linux: Boolean fields indicating platform availability.
  • Metacritic score: Score from Metacritic.
  • Metacritic url: URL to the Metacritic page for the game.
  • User score: User score for the game.
  • Positive: Number of positive reviews.
  • Negative: Number of negative reviews.
  • Score rank: Ranking of the game based on score.
  • Achievements: Number of achievements in the game.
  • Recommendations: Number of recommendations for the game.
  • Notes: Additional notes about the game.
  • Average playtime forever: Average total playtime across all players.
  • Average playtime two weeks: Average playtime in the last two weeks.
  • Median playtime forever: Median total playtime across all players.
  • Median playtime two weeks: Median playtime in the last two weeks.
  • Developers: Developers of the game.
  • Publishers: Publishers of the game.
  • Categories: Categories of the game.
  • Genres: Genres of the game.
  • Tags: Tags associated with the game.
  • Screenshots: URLs to screenshots of the game.
  • Movies: URLs to trailers or movies of the game.

These columns provide a comprehensive overview of each game, including its reception, content, and technical details.

We can see that there are null values in the dataset at many places. We can drop the Metacritic information as it null and of no use and Metacritic url is linked with Metacritic score as whenever there is a value in Metacritic url column, only then there is a valuen in Metacritic score column and otherwise its just "0" which is just false informtion in many cases. Further we can also drop "Website", "Support url", "Support Email", "Screentshots", "Movies" and "Header Image" as it contains only urls and many null values as well and we cannot use imputation to add values to this data and also it is not of much use.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

1. Trend Analysis: Game Genres Popularity¶

In [16]:
# Extracting year from "Release date"
data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Release date'], errors='coerce').dt.year
In [17]:
# One game has multiple genres so we are splitting them and creating a new row for each genre of each game
exploded_genres = data.dropna(subset=['Genres']).copy()
exploded_genres['Genres'] = exploded_genres['Genres'].apply(lambda x: x.split(','))
exploded_genres = exploded_genres.explode('Genres')
In [19]:
# Grouping data by year and genres
year_genre_counts = exploded_genres.groupby(['Year', 'Genres']).size().reset_index(name='Count')
print(year_genre_counts)

In [21]:
# Visualization
sns.set(style='whitegrid')
pivot_data = year_genre_counts.pivot(index='Year', columns='Genres', values='Count').fillna(0)
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
for column in pivot_data.columns:
    plt.plot(pivot_data.index, pivot_data[column], marker='', linewidth=2, label=column)

plt.title('Trends in Game Genre Popularity Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Games Released')
plt.legend(title='Genres', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

This plot shows the yearly total of games launched in each genre. We can see how the popularity of each genre has changed over time by looking at the lines that represent the various genres. Trends such as rises or falls in the quantity of games launched in particular genres are visible. "Indie", "Casual" and "Adventure" games have seen high popularity.

With respect to price and average playtime, this graphic displays the distribution of games over time. The scatter plot's dispersion of points over different price ranges and lack of identifiable pattern implies that there isn't a strong linear relationship between a game's pricing and the average amount of time people spend playing it.

The distribution of data points over the pricing range suggests that user reception varies depending on the cost of the game.

5. Trend with adult content in the games.¶

One observatiion that we made was that "Notes" column contains 13,021 values in it and rest all were null values. But intrestingly, we found that each time there was a note mentioned for a particular game, its intentions were to make the users aware about or give warning for either sexual content, abusive language, violence, drug use, alcohol comsumption, blood shed, etc. which indicates that the game is suggested to be played by adults above 18 years of age.

In [65]:
# Convert 'Release date' to datetime and extract the year
data['Release Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Release date'], errors='coerce').dt.year

# Filter rows where 'Notes' column contains 'adult'
adult = data[data['Notes'].str.contains('adult', case=False, na=False)]

# Count the number of adult games per year
games_adult_per_year = adult.groupby('Release Year').size()
In [66]:
# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5), facecolor='white')
plt.plot(games_adult_per_year.index, games_adult_per_year.values, marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.title('Number of Adult Games Over the Years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Adult Games')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

This line graph illustrates the number of games released each year that are specifically noted as being for adults. We can see the increase in the number of adult games over the years and the graph goes down around the year 2023 because there is not enough data for games launched that year.

Conclusion¶

From the perspective of business, these visualizations provide the following insights for both Steam users and game developers:

Popularity of Genres and Development Focus: A robust market demand for games in the "Indie," "Casual," and "Adventure" genres is indicated by their popularity. To potentially capitalize on current player interest, game developers should think about concentrating their efforts on creating games in these genres.
Market Trends and Adaptation: Game creators can keep up with current trends in the market by keeping an eye on how the popularity of a genre changes over time. Remaining competitive in the market may depend on developers responding to these trends by refocusing their efforts on developing games in emerging genres or altering current releases to suit evolving player tastes.
Price-Playtime link: It appears that basing prices exclusively on projected playtime may not be the best course of action because there is no discernible linear link between average playtime and game pricing. When deciding on pricing options, game makers should take into account a number of aspects, including target demographic, genre, and quality.
Ownership and User Reviews: The value of user involvement and feedback is highlighted by the association between the number of user reviews and the expected number of game owners. Boosting user reviews and cultivating a strong rapport with the player base can help games on the platform become more visible, sell more, and be more successful overall.
Adult Content and Target Audience: There appears to be a rising market for games with mature themes, as seen by the rise in adult-themed games over time and the frequency of content warnings. It is imperative for game producers to use caution while creating material, taking into account the tastes and interests of adult players.
Platform-Specific Points to Remember: The difference in game prices between operating systems emphasizes how crucial it is to comprehend platform-specific market dynamics. It is recommended that game developers and the Steam platform customize their pricing plans and promotional tactics to accommodate variations in player behavior and purchasing power among different operating systems.

To sum up, these observations highlight how important it is for game developers and the Steam platform to be aware of the market, engage players, and make strategic decisions. Developers can better position their games for success in a competitive and dynamic gaming landscape by utilizing these findings, and platforms such as Steam can adapt their services and features to better suit the varied demands and tastes of their user base.
